The dataset is based on NYC yellow taxi cap. Total of 132 files, 2009-01 to 2019-12. (Link https://www1.nyc.gov/site/tlc/about/tlc-trip-record-data.page) The data is gathered with bash scrip with wget command to a personal computer. Due to the size of the dataset, the Purdue scholar is not suitable due to space limitation.

Month data of taxi dataset also provides large number of data, ex. 2017-06 has 9,656,995 entries. The overwhelming of data entries requires clearer graphical analysis. There are several examples within this document that outliers and bad graphical analysis shows no room to interprete the data correctly.

The graph shows that 1 to 2 mile trip distance is most common. The dataset has 0.01, 0.02, hundredth precision in miles. With further processing, the dataset can be simplified into 1, 2, 3 miles, bigger bin width size. However I believe to represent the full resolution of the dataset is more valuable to find the most common distance.

totalavgdist <-read.csv("/Users/taesuplee/taxi_data/totaldist.txt",header=F, sep=" ")
totalavgdist <-as.data.frame(totalavgdist)
colnames(totalavgdist) <- c('date','avgdist')
totalavgdist$date <- as.Date(as.character(totalavgdist$date), format='%Y%m%d')

ggplot(totalavgdist, aes(x= date,y= avgdist))+ 
  geom_point(shape=18, color="blue")+
   labs(title =  "Average monthly trip distance for 10 years")+xlab("Date")+ylab("Trip distance(miles)")

Average distance is computed within shell envrionment again. Awk commend is used to get distance data and average the distance data. All the output is collected to txt file. Once the operation is completed, the txt file is loaded into R to create a plot. This operation is performed on a PC.

#!/bin/zsh for year in {09..19}; do for month in {01..12}; do #Average distance of rides per month cat yellow_tripdata_20\(year-\)month.csv | awk -F, ’BEGIN{} {avgdis = avgdis+ \(5} END{print avgdis/NR}' >> 20\)year-avg.txt

rides <-read.csv("/Users/taesuplee/taxi_data/route_09-01.csv", header=F, sep=" ")

## Warning: Removed 36729 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Performed plotting 1 month(09-2001) pickup locations against the NY manhattan map. Due to high activity for 30 days, the NY manhattan map is complete black.

Below command is commputing date information into single number string. Single block of numbers can be handled much easier than the original format, 2017-06-08 08:01:32. The command awk checks time window with given condition. To create visual representation, time window should be reduced to 1 hour or 5 hours of a day. The current time window is 30 days and 0900 to 1200 hours only. Pre-processing is also required for awk to work. SED command removes the end of the line.

#!/bin/zsh for year in {09..19}; do for month in {01..12}; do sed -e “s//g” yellow_tripdata_20\(year-\)month.csv > 20\(year-\)month.csv #extract routes info for each month 1 - 30th 0900 to 1200 filename=20\({year}-\){month}.csv year=\(year month=\)month awk -F, -v month=“\(month" -v year="\)year” -v filename=“$filename” ‘{gsub(“-”, "“,$2);gsub(” “,”“,$2);gsub(”:“,”",\(2)} 20'\)year’‘$month’01090000 <= \(2 && 20'\)year’‘$month’30120000 >= $2’ \(filename > route_\)year-$month.csv

daily <-read.csv("/Users/taesuplee/taxi_data/daily_rides.txt", sep= " ", colClasses = c("integer", "Date"), header = TRUE)

Daily taxi rides were performed in Z shell envrionment. Below commands were used. #!/bin/zsh for year in {09..19}; do for month in {01..12}; #for number of taxi rides on each day #cat yellow_tripdata_20\(year-\)month.csv | awk -F, ‘{print $2}’ |awk -F" " ‘{print $1}’| sort | uniq -c | sort -k 2,2 >> daily_rides.txt

ggplot(daily, aes(x= Dates,y= Rides))+ 
  geom_point(shape=18, color="blue")+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se= FALSE, linetype="dashed", color="darkred", fill="blue") + labs(title =  "Daily rides for 10 years")+xlab("Dates") + ylab("Number of rides")

monthly <- aggregate( x= daily$Rides, by=list(format(daily$Dates ,"%Y-%m")) , FUN="mean")
colnames(monthly) <- c('monthYear','monthlyValue')
monthly$monthYear <-paste0(monthly$monthYear,"-01")
monthly$monthYear <- as.Date(monthly$monthYear)
